    "summary": "OPTIONAL — only if right person, Preface is sufficient alone",
    "content": "**OPTIONAL.** The Translator's Preface now does everything a reader needs to enter the collection. A Foreword would add legitimacy and cross-traditional positioning (someone who can say \"this converges with Husserl/Nagarjuna/Wittgenstein in ways the author did not set out to achieve\"), but only if the right person writes it — someone who can speak to the philosophical significance without domesticating the work into any single tradition. A bad Foreword (one that frames the collection as \"Eastern philosophy meets Western formalism\" or reduces it to commentary on established figures) would actively harm the reader's experience. If the right person is available, yes. If not, the Preface is sufficient and the collection stands on its own."
  }
}
